---
title: Mapo Tofu (麻婆豆腐)
source: Serious Eats / J. Kenji López-Alt
servings: 4
tags:
  - chinese
  - sichuan
  - spicy
  - tofu
  - vegetarian option
---

Cut @firm tofu{14%oz}(drained) into 3/4-inch cubes. Gently simmer in salted
water in a #medium saucepan{} for ~{10%minutes}. Drain and set aside.

> Simmering the tofu in salted water seasons it throughout and firms the
> texture so it doesn't crumble.

In a #wok{} or large skillet, heat @vegetable oil{2%tbsp} over high heat until
shimmering. Add @ground pork{8%oz} and cook, breaking into small pieces, for
~{5%minutes} until browned and crispy.

Add @doubanjiang{2%tbsp}(Pixian brand preferred) and @fermented black beans{1%tbsp}(rinsed, chopped).
Stir-fry for ~{1%minute} until fragrant and oil turns red.

Add @garlic{4%cloves}(minced) and @ginger{1%tbsp}(minced). Cook ~{30%seconds}.

Pour in @chicken stock{1%cup} and @soy sauce{1%tbsp}. Bring to a boil.

Gently slide in the tofu. Simmer for ~{5%minutes}.

Mix @cornstarch{1%tbsp} with @water{2%tbsp} to make a slurry. Stir into the wok.
Cook until thickened, about ~{1%minute}.

Remove from heat. Stir in @sesame oil{1%tsp} and @Sichuan peppercorn powder{1%tsp}(freshly ground).

Garnish with @scallions{2}(thinly sliced) and serve immediately over @steamed rice{}.
